Dragon Ball Supervised Learning Classification¶

Problem Definition¶

Can we accurately predict whether a Dragon Ball character will win or lose a fight based on their attributes such as Power Level, Race, Transformations, Techniques, and Previous Battles?

Context¶

  • In the Dragon Ball universe, battles are determined by various factors, including a fighter’s power level, race, transformations, fighting techniques, and experience.
  • Using machine learning classification models, we can estimate the probability of winning based on these attributes.
  • This could be useful for game balancing, AI-driven character matchups, competitive strategy analysis, and fan discussions.

Objective¶

  • Develop a classification model to predict whether a character will win or lose a battle.
  • Identify key features that contribute the most to battle outcomes.
  • Compare the performance of different models (Logistic Regression, Random Forest, XGBoost, and SVM) to determine the best approach.
  • Analyze how race, transformations, and fighting styles impact battle success.

Data Dictionary¶

  • Name: Character's name
  • Race: The species of the fighter (Saiyan, Namekian, etc.)
  • Gender: Male or Female
  • Power Level: The numeric power level (Target Variable)
  • Y Variable (Target)
  • Ki Blast: Character’s energy attack technique
  • Melee Combat: Fighting style and close-combat abilities
  • Speed: Speed level (Numeric)
  • Special Attack: Ultimate moves or techniques
  • Transformation: The highest transformation level achieved (Super Saiyan, etc.)
  • Speed_Original: Descriptive speed category (Fast, Medium, Slow)
  • Normalized_Power: Scaled power level (0-1)
  • Power_Score: Normalized score based on battle metrics
  • Meta: Combined metadata of character attributes

Create Win/Loss Column¶

Generate All Possible Matchups

In [321]:
from itertools import combinations

# Generate all possible matchups
battle_pairs = list(combinations(data.index, 2))

# Create a DataFrame for battles
battle_df = pd.DataFrame(battle_pairs, columns=['Character_1', 'Character_2'])

# Merge attributes from the original dataset for both characters
battle_df = battle_df.merge(data, left_on='Character_1', right_index=True, suffixes=('_1', ''))
battle_df = battle_df.merge(data, left_on='Character_2', right_index=True, suffixes=('_1', '_2'))

# Assign winner based on power level, speed, and transformation level
battle_df['Winner'] = np.where(
    (battle_df['Power Level_1'] > battle_df['Power Level_2']) |
    ((battle_df['Power Level_1'] == battle_df['Power Level_2']) & (battle_df['Speed_1'] > battle_df['Speed_2'])) |
    ((battle_df['Power Level_1'] == battle_df['Power Level_2']) &
     (battle_df['Speed_1'] == battle_df['Speed_2']) &
     (battle_df['Transformation_Level_1'] > battle_df['Transformation_Level_2'])),
    battle_df['Character_1'],  # Character_1 wins
    battle_df['Character_2']   # Character_2 wins
)

Calculate Each Character's Win Rate

In [322]:
# Count wins for each character
win_counts = battle_df['Winner'].value_counts().reset_index()
win_counts.columns = ['Character', 'Wins']

# Count total battles for each character
total_battles = pd.concat([battle_df['Character_1'], battle_df['Character_2']]).value_counts().reset_index()
total_battles.columns = ['Character', 'Total_Battles']

# Merge win counts with total battles
win_loss_stats = total_battles.merge(win_counts, on='Character', how='left').fillna(0)

# Compute win rate
win_loss_stats['Win_Rate'] = win_loss_stats['Wins'] / win_loss_stats['Total_Battles']
win_loss_stats.drop(columns=['Wins'], inplace=True)

# Convert win rate into a binary target: 1 if win rate > 0.5, else 0
win_loss_stats['Win_Loss_Label'] = (win_loss_stats['Win_Rate'] > 0.5).astype(int)
  • Character_1_Wins = 1 → Character_1 won
  • Character_1_Wins = 0 → Character_2 won

Merge Datasets

In [323]:
# Merge win/loss stats into original dataset
data = data.merge(win_loss_stats[['Character', 'Win_Loss_Label']], left_index=True, right_on='Character', how='left')

# Drop redundant 'Character' column after merging (if necessary)
data.drop(columns=['Character'], inplace=True)

Model evaluation criterion¶

The Model Can Make Two Types of Wrong Predictions:

  • False Positive (FP): Predicting that a character will win when they actually lose.
  • False Negative (FN): Predicting that a character will lose when they actually win.

Which Case is More Important?

  • The more critical error is False Negative (FN) because:
    • If the model predicts that a character will lose, but they actually win, it fails to identify strong characters correctly.
    • This is a major issue in battle prediction because missing a strong character could lead to incorrect tournament brackets or rankings.
    • FN means underestimating a fighter's strength, which can negatively affect predictions in battles.

How to Reduce False Negatives?

  • The goal is to maximize Recall, ensuring that the model correctly identifies as many winning characters as possible.
  • Higher recall means fewer missed wins (False Negatives), leading to better predictions of strong contenders.
  • If Recall is high, the model is less likely to underestimate powerful characters.

Key Metric: Recall (Sensitivity / True Positive Rate)

  • Use Cases:
    • Important when missing a winning character is more critical.
    • Ensures that strong characters are correctly classified as winners.
    • Useful when identifying battle outcomes where underestimating a fighter’s strength could lead to poor predictions.

Create a function to calculate and print the classification report and the confusion matrix so that we don't have to rewrite the same code repeatedly for each model.

In [337]:
# Creating metric function

def metrics_score(actual, predicted):

    print(classification_report(actual, predicted)) # print classification report (precision, recall, accuracy, etc...)

    cm = confusion_matrix(actual, predicted)

    plt.figure(figsize = (8, 5))

    #sns.heatmap(cm, annot = True, fmt = '.2f', xticklabels = ['Not Attriate', 'Attriate'], yticklabels = ['Not Attriate', 'Attriate'])
    sns.heatmap(cm, annot=True, fmt=".2f", xticklabels=["Loss", "Win"], yticklabels=["Loss", "Win"])
    plt.ylabel('Actual')

    plt.xlabel('Predicted')

    plt.show()
In [338]:
def model_performance_classification(model, predictors, target):
    """
    Function to compute different metrics to check classification model performance

    model: classifier

    predictors: independent variables

    target: dependent variable
    """

    # Predicting using the independent variables
    pred = model.predict(predictors)

    recall = recall_score(target, pred,average = 'macro')                 # To compute recall

    precision = precision_score(target, pred, average = 'macro')              # To compute precision

    acc = accuracy_score(target, pred)                                 # To compute accuracy score


    # Creating a dataframe of metrics

    df_perf = pd.DataFrame(
        {
            "Precision":  precision,
            "Recall":  recall,
            "Accuracy": acc,
        },

        index = [0],
    )

    return df_perf

Tuning the Decision Tree Classifier using GridSearch¶

  • Hyperparameter tuning is tricky in the sense that there is no direct way to calculate how a change in the hyperparameter value will reduce the loss of your model, so we usually resort to experimentation. We'll use Grid search to perform hyperparameter tuning.

  • Grid search is a tuning technique that attempts to compute the optimum values of hyperparameters.

  • It is an exhaustive search that is performed on the specific parameter values of a model. The parameters of the estimator/model used to apply these methods are optimized by cross-validated grid-search over a parameter grid.

  • Criterion{“gini”, “entropy”}

    • The function is to measure the quality of a split. Supported criteria are “gini” for the Gini impurity and “entropy” for the information gain.

  • max_depth

    • The maximum depth of the tree. If None, then nodes are expanded until all leaves are pure or until all leaves contain less than min_samples_split samples.

  • min_samples_leaf

    • The minimum number of samples is required to be at a leaf node. A split point at any depth will only be considered if it leaves at least min_samples_leaf training samples in each of the left and right branches. This may have the effect of smoothing the model, especially in regression.
In [349]:
from sklearn.metrics import classification_report, confusion_matrix, recall_score
from sklearn.model_selection import GridSearchCV

#%%time
# Choose the type of classifier
dtree_tuned = DecisionTreeClassifier(random_state = 1)

# Grid of parameters to choose from
parameters = {'max_depth': np.arange(2, 7), # should test a wide range of values 2, 15, 50, 100
              'criterion': ['gini', 'entropy'],
              'min_samples_leaf': [5, 10, 20, 25]}

# Type of scoring used to compare parameter combinations.
# "pos_label": It allows you to specify which class label should be considered as the positive class when calculating the scoring metric.
# By default, pos_label = 1, but you can change it based on your specific use case.
scorer = metrics.make_scorer(recall_score, pos_label = 1)

# Grid search object
gridCV = GridSearchCV(dtree_tuned, parameters, scoring = scorer, cv = 10) # cross validation, GridSearchCV to tune hyperparameters

# Fitting the grid search on the train data
gridCV = gridCV.fit(x_train, y_train)

Random Forest¶

  • Building the Random Forest Classifier
  • Random Forest is a bagging algorithm where the base models are Decision Trees. Samples are taken from the training data and on each sample, a decision tree makes a prediction.
  • The results from all the decision trees are combined and the final prediction is made using voting (for classification problems) or averaging (for regression problems).

Tuning the Random Forest classifier using GridSearch¶

  • n_estimators: The number of trees in the forest.

  • min_samples_split: The minimum number of samples required to split an internal node.

  • min_samples_leaf: The minimum number of samples required to be at a leaf node.

  • max_features{“auto”, “sqrt”, “log2”, 'None'}: The number of features to consider when looking for the best split.

    • If “auto”, then max_features=sqrt(n_features).
    • If “sqrt”, then max_features=sqrt(n_features) (same as “auto”).
    • If “log2”, then max_features=log2(n_features).
    • If None, then max_features=n_features.
In [368]:
%%time
# Choose the type of classifier
rf_estimator_tuned = RandomForestClassifier(random_state = 1)

# Grid of parameters to choose from
params_rf = {"n_estimators": [100, 250, 500],
             "min_samples_leaf": np.arange(1, 4, 1),
             "max_features": [0.7, 0.9, 'auto']} # max features: number of features to randomly select from data set (.7 is 70% of features to 90%)

# Type of scoring used to compare parameter combinations - recall score for class 1
scorer = metrics.make_scorer(recall_score, pos_label = 1)

# Run the grid search
grid_obj = GridSearchCV(rf_estimator_tuned, params_rf, scoring = scorer, cv = 5)

grid_obj = grid_obj.fit(x_train, y_train)

# Set the classifier to the best combination of parameters
rf_estimator_tuned = grid_obj.best_estimator_

Hyperparameter Tuning: Boosting¶

Hyperparameter tuning is a great technique in machine learning to develop the model with optimal parameters. If the size of the data increases, the computation time will increase during the training process.

  • For practice purposes, we have listed below some of the important hyperparameters for each algorithm that can be tuned to improve the model performance.

Adaboost

  • Some important hyperparameters that can be tuned:
    • base_estimator object, default = None The base estimator from which the boosted ensemble is built. Support for sample weighting is required, as well as proper classes_ and n_classes_ attributes. If None, then the base estimator is DecisionTreeClassifier initialized with max_depth=1
    • n_estimators int, default = 50 The maximum number of estimators at which boosting is terminated. In the case of a perfect fit, the learning procedure is stopped early.
    • learning_rate float, default = 1.0 Weight is applied to each classifier at each boosting iteration. A higher learning rate increases the contribution of each classifier.

Gradient Boosting Algorithm

  • Some important hyperparameters that can be tuned:
    • n_estimators: The number of boosting stages that will be performed.
    • max_depth: Limits the number of nodes in the tree. The best value depends on the interaction of the input variables.
    • min_samples_split: The minimum number of samples required to split an internal node.
    • learning_rate: How much the contribution of each tree will shrink.
    • loss:Loss function to optimize.

XGBoost Algorithm

  • Some important hyperparameters that can be tuned:
    • booster [default = gbtree ] Which booster to use. Can be gbtree, gblinear, or dart; gbtree and dart use tree-based models while gblinear uses linear functions.
    • min_child_weight [default = 1]
      • The minimum sum of instance weight (hessian) needed in a child. If the tree partition step results in a leaf node with the sum of instance weight less than min_child_weight, then the building process will give up further partitioning.The larger min_child_weight is, the more conservative the algorithm will be.

  • Observation
    • All Models Have Perfect Scores
      • Precision, Recall, and Accuracy are all 1.0 (100%) across every classifier.
      • This suggests that the models are predicting all test cases correctly without errors.
    • Potential Overfitting
      • A perfect score is highly unusual in real-world datasets and may indicate overfitting.
      • Overfitting can occur when a model learns patterns too specifically to the training data and lacks generalization.
    • Possible Data Leakage or Issues
      • If the dataset is too small, the models might be memorizing patterns instead of generalizing.
      • Check for data leakage, such as test data being influenced by training data.
      • Ensure features make sense and there aren’t any duplicated or leaking variables.
    • Balanced Dataset and Simple Patterns?
      • If the dataset is perfectly balanced and contains highly separable features, such perfect scores might be valid.
      • However, real-world classification tasks usually involve some misclassifications.

Conclusoin¶

The models achieved perfect classification performance across all metrics (precision, recall, accuracy) on both training and test datasets. This suggests that the models are likely overfitting, especially given that real-world datasets rarely result in such perfect scores. The feature importance analysis also showed that the model assigns zero importance to all features, further indicating potential issues in the training process.

Recommendations¶

  • Verify Data Preprocessing: Check if features are correctly formatted and properly scaled. Ensure no data leakage from the target variable.
  • Reduce Overfitting: Implement techniques such as regularization, pruning (for decision trees), and hyperparameter tuning.
  • Feature Engineering: Reassess feature selection to ensure meaningful input variables are contributing to predictions. Cross-Validation: Use k-fold cross-validation to get a more reliable estimate of model performance. Test on Unseen Data: Evaluate models on a separate validation dataset to ensure generalizability.
